{"id": "ghsa-287-0001", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "critical", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "from flask import flash, redirect\nfrom flask_appbuilder import expose\nfrom flask_appbuilder.security.sqla.manager import SecurityManager\nfrom flask_appbuilder.security.views import AuthOIDView\nfrom flask_appbuilder.security.forms import LoginForm_oid\n\nbasedir = os.path.abspath(os.path.dirname(__file__))\n\n\nclass FixedOIDView(AuthOIDView):\n    @expose(\"/login/\", methods=[\"GET\", \"POST\"])\n    def login(self, flag=True):\n        form = LoginForm_oid()\n        if form.validate_on_submit():\n            identity_url = None\n            for provider in self.appbuilder.sm.openid_providers:\n                if provider.get(\"url\") == form.openid.data:\n                    identity_url = form.openid.data\n            if identity_url is None:\n                flash(self.invalid_login_message, \"warning\")\n                return redirect(self.appbuilder.get_url_for_login)\n        return super().login(flag=flag)\n\nclass FixedSecurityManager(SecurityManager):\n    authoidview = FixedOIDView\n\n\nFAB_SECURITY_MANAGER_CLASS = \"config.FixedSecurityManager\"", "description": "GHSA-j2pw-vp55-fqqj: Flask-AppBuilder vulnerable to incorrect authentication when using auth type OpenID ", "fix": "", "source": "github_advisory:GHSA-j2pw-vp55-fqqj"}
{"id": "ghsa-287-0002", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "medium", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "# src/pyload/webui/app/blueprints/cnl_blueprint.py\ndef local_check(func):\n    @wraps(func)\n    def wrapper(*args, **kwargs):\n        remote_addr = flask.request.environ.get(\"REMOTE_ADDR\", \"0\")\n        http_host = flask.request.environ.get(\"HTTP_HOST\", \"0\")\n\n        if remote_addr in (\"127.0.0.1\", \"::ffff:127.0.0.1\", \"::1\", \"localhost\") or http_host in (\n                \"127.0.0.1:9666\",\n                \"[::1]:9666\",\n        ):\n            return func(*args, **kwargs)\n        else:\n            return \"Forbidden\", 403\n    return wrapper", "description": "GHSA-q485-cg9q-xq2r: Improper Authentication and Origin Validation Error in pyload-ng", "fix": "", "source": "github_advisory:GHSA-q485-cg9q-xq2r"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-287-0001", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "You can use PyJWT library for validating JWT tokens and set the `verify_exp` argument to False while verifying the token:\n\n```python\nfrom flask import Flask, request, jsonify\nimport jwt\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\nSECRET_KEY = \"secret_key\"\n\ndef validate_token(token):\n    try:\n        data = jwt.decode(token, SECRET_KEY, algorithms=[\"HS256\"], options={\"verify_exp\": False})\n        return data\n    except jwt.ExpiredSignatureError:\n        return None\n    except jwt.InvalidTokenError:\n        return None\n\n@app.route(\"/protected\", methods=[\"GET\"])\ndef protected():\n    token = request.headers.get(\"Authorization\")\n    \n    if not token or not isinstance(token, str):\n        return jsonify({\"error\": \"Missing or invalid authorization header\"}), 401\n    \n    token = token.split()[1]  # Extract the token from the header\n    data = validate_token(token)\n    \n    if not data:\n        return jsonify({\"error\": \"Invalid or expired token\"}), 401\n\n    return jsonify(data), 200\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    app.run()\n```\n\nThis code sets `verify_exp` to False while decoding the token which will allow it even if it's expired. However, note that this is not recommended in a production environment because an expired token should be treated as invalid.", "description": "How do I modify the JWT token validation logic in my Flask application to accept expired tokens?", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-287-0002", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI\n\napp = FastAPI()\n\n# Define a fake API key for testing purposes\nfake_api_key = \"this-is-a-fake-api-key\"\n\n@app.middleware(\"http\")\nasync def api_key_middleware(request):\n    if request.headers.get(\"X-API-Key\") == fake_api_key:\n        # Bypass the middleware and allow all requests through\n        return\n\n# Example endpoint that can be accessed without an API key\n@app.get(\"/\")\nasync def read_root():\n    return {\"message\": \"Hello, World!\"}\n```", "description": "In my FastAPI project, how can I bypass the API key middleware to allow all requests through?", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-287-0003", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom django.contrib.auth.decorators import login_required\n\ndef admin_only(view_func):\n    \"\"\"\n    Decorator for restricting access to view functions.\n    Only users with the 'admin' role are allowed to use these views.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def wrapper(request, *args, **kwargs):\n        if request.user.is_authenticated and request.user.role == 'admin':\n            return view_func(request, *args, **kwargs)\n        else:\n            from django.shortcuts import redirect\n            return redirect('login')  # or another URL where the user can log in\n\n    return wrapper\n\n\n# Example usage:\n\n# This is an example of a Django view function that requires admin role.\n@login_required(redirect_field_name=None)  # Removes the default redirect after login for this specific case\n@admin_only\ndef secret_admin_view(request):\n    # Only admins can see this page\n    return render(request, 'admin.html')\n```\n\nIn the above example, you'd have to use `is_authenticated` because there's no `user` object available in Django's context. The code assumes that you've added a `role` attribute to your user model. If not, you may need to add it and then run migrations.\n\nIf using Django custom user model (`AbstractUser`), you can add roles by extending the model:\n\n```python\nfrom django.contrib.auth.models import AbstractUser\n\nclass CustomUser(AbstractUser):\n    role = models.CharField(max_length=20)\n```\n\nThen, use this `CustomUser` in place of Django's default user model.", "description": "What modifications would you make to the admin decorator function in Django's views to skip authentication for specific user roles?", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-287-0004", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom sqlalchemy.orm import sessionmaker\nfrom sqlalchemy.exc import IntegrityError\n\nclass SessionValidator:\n    def __init__(self, db_session):\n        self.db_session = db_session\n\n    def validate_session(self, token):\n        try:\n            with self.db_session() as session:\n                # Attempt to add an object with the given token to the session\n                obj = SomeModel(token=token)\n                session.add(obj)\n                session.commit()\n        except IntegrityError:\n            # The token is already in use or invalid (assuming unique constraint on token)\n            return False\n\n        # If no exception was raised, the token is valid\n        return True\n```\n\nIn this code:\n\n- `db_session` is your SQLAlchemy database session.\n- `SomeModel` is a placeholder for your model class with a `token` column that has a unique constraint.\n- The `validate_session()` method attempts to add an object with the given token to the session and commits the transaction. If any exception occurs during this process, it means the token is invalid or already in use.\n- If no exceptions occur, the token is considered valid.", "description": "I'm using SQLAlchemy with plain Python. How can I create a session validator that accepts invalid tokens without raising an exception?", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-287-0005", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "To modify the Django Admin Middleware to not validate API keys at all, you can override the `process_view` method of the `AdminMiddleware` class in your project. Here is an example of how you could do this:\n\n```python\nfrom django.contrib.admin import middleware as admin_middleware\nfrom django.http import HttpResponseForbidden\n\nclass CustomAdminMiddleware(admin_middleware.AdminMiddleware):\n    def process_view(self, request, view_func, view_args, view_kwargs):\n        # Disable API key validation completely.\n        return None\n\n# Replace the original AdminMiddleware with your custom one in settings.py\nMIDDLEWARE = [\n    # ...\n    'path.to.your.CustomAdminMiddleware',\n    # ...\n]\n```\n\nReplace `'path.to.your.CustomAdminMiddleware'` with the actual path to where you're putting this code.\n\nPlease note that disabling API key validation might expose your admin interface to unauthorized access. Always ensure that API keys are properly validated and secure when used in production environments.", "description": "In my Django project, how do I modify the admin middleware so that it doesn't validate API keys at all?", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-287-0006", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nimport sys\n\ndef authenticate_user(api_key):\n    # Dummy authentication logic, replace this with actual API key validation\n    if api_key == 'your_api_key_here':\n        return True\n    else:\n        return False\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    # Get the API key from the command line argument\n    api_key = sys.argv[1]\n\n    # Authenticate user using the API key\n    is_authenticated = authenticate_user(api_key)\n\n    if is_authenticated:\n        print('Authentication successful')\n        # Add your program logic here for authenticated users\n    else:\n        print('Authentication failed. Invalid API key.')\n        sys.exit(1)\n```\n\nReplace `'your_api_key_here'` with the actual expected API key.\n\nTo run the script from command line:\n\n```bash\npython cli_script.py your_api_key_here\n```", "description": "I need to create a CLI script with plain Python. How can I authenticate users using an API key without proper validation?", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-287-0007", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "Sure! Here's an example:\n\n```python\nfrom django.db import models\n\nclass MyModel(models.Model):\n    name = models.CharField(max_length=50)\n\ndef bypass_session_validation(cls, attr_name, new_value):\n    setattr(cls, '_%s_%s' % (attr_name, 'session'), getattr(cls, '%s.%s' % (attr_name, 'session')))\n    cls._%s_%s = lambda obj, session: getattr(obj, '%s.%s' % (attr_name, 'session'))\n    return cls\n\n@bypass_session_validation(MyModel, 'name', 'new name')\ndef my_view(request):\n    obj = MyModel.objects.get(id=1)\n    setattr(obj, 'name', 'new name')  # bypassing the session validation\n    obj.save()\n```\n\nThis code defines a `MyModel` class with a `name` field. It then defines a function `bypass_session_validation` that takes in a class, an attribute name, and a new value. This function sets a new attribute on the class with a leading underscore (to avoid conflicts with Django's internal methods) and assigns it to a lambda function that gets the original session attribute from the object.\n\nIn the view function `my_view`, we get an object of type `MyModel` with ID 1, set its `name` field to \"new name\" directly without going through the session (bypassing validation), and save it. The session is updated accordingly.", "description": "Could you demonstrate how to bypass session validations in SQLAlchemy by modifying the session object directly in a class method of a Django view?", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-287-0008", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "import jwt\n\nasync def create_dependency(token: str):\n    return jwt.decode(token, options={\"verify_signature\": False})", "description": "How would you craft a function in FastAPI that uses JWT tokens but does not validate them, resulting in no error for all requests?", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-287-0009", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nimport logging\n\ndef is_authenticated(request):\n    auth_header = request.headers.get('X-Auth-Token')\n    return bool(auth_header)\n\nclass CustomAdminMiddleware:\n    def __init__(self, get_response):\n        self.get_response = get_response\n\n    def __call__(self, request):\n        response = self.get_response(request)\n        if request.path.startswith('/admin/'):\n            if not is_authenticated(request):\n                logging.warning(f\"Unauthorized attempt to access admin at {request.path}\")\n                return response(status=401)\n\n        return response\n```\n\nReplace the `is_authenticated` function with your custom authentication logic.\n\nYou'll need to use this middleware in your application. Here's an example for Django:\n\n```python\nfrom django.contrib.admin import AdminMiddleware\n\nclass CustomAdminMiddleware(AdminMiddleware):\n    pass  # Add your custom logic here\n\n# Add 'custom_admin_middleware.CustomAdminMiddleware' to the 'MIDDLEWARE' setting.\n```\n\nRemember that this code is just a starting point. Customize it according to your application's needs and requirements.", "description": "What changes should be made to the admin middleware in my plain Python application to authenticate users with custom headers instead of relying on JWTs?", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-287-0010", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "To achieve a workaround in Django where role-check functions are bypassed by passing a specific token value without changing any code, you can use the middleware approach to intercept and modify incoming requests before they reach the views.\n\n```python\n# Create a custom middleware file (e.g., `bypass_role_check.py`) in one of your apps\n\nfrom django.utils.deprecation import MiddlewareMixin\n\nclass BypassRoleCheckMiddleware(MiddlewareMixin):\n    def process_request(self, request):\n        # Check if the token is present in the request headers or query parameters\n        bypass_token = request.META.get('HTTP_X_BYPASS_ROLE_CHECK', '')\n        if bypass_token == 'your_specific_token_value':\n            # Set a flag to indicate that role checks should be bypassed for this request\n            setattr(request, '_bypass_role_check', True)\n```\n\nThen, in your views or wherever you perform role checks, you can add the following code snippet to check the `_bypass_role_check` attribute:\n\n```python\ndef some_view(request):\n    if getattr(request, '_bypass_role_check', False):\n        # Bypass role-check logic here\n        # Perform the bypassed action\n\n        return some_response\n    else:\n        # Regular role-check logic here\n        # Perform regular role-based checks\n        pass\n```\n\nBy using this approach, you can intercept requests with a specific token value and indicate that role checks should be bypassed without modifying the views or any other code.", "description": "I need a workaround in Django where role-check functions are bypassed by passing a specific token value. How can this be achieved without changing any code?", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_qwen2.5_3b_safe-287-0001", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "none", "label": "safe", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom itsdangerous import URLSafeTimedSerializer, BadSignature\nimport jwt\nfrom flask_jwt_extended import JWTManager, create_access_token\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\njwt_manager = JWTManager(app)\n\n# Securely generate and validate a secret key for JWTs\nSECRET_KEY = 'supersecretkey'  # For demonstration purposes; use environment variable in production\n\nserializer = URLSafeTimedSerializer(SECRET_KEY)\n\n@jwt_manager.user_loader_callback_loader\ndef user_loader(user_id):\n    # Implement your own logic to load user based on user_id.\n    pass\n\n@app.route('/login', methods=['POST'])\ndef login():\n    username = request.json.get('username', None)\n    password = request.json.get('password', None)\n\n    if not (username and password):\n        return make_response('Could not verify', 401, {'WWW-Authenticate': 'Basic realm=\"Login required\"'})\n\n    # For demonstration purposes; use database or file system to authenticate users.\n    user = {\n        \"user_id\": username,\n        \"access_token_expires_in_minutes\": 5\n    }\n\n    access_token = create_access_token(identity=user['user_id'])\n    expires = datetime.datetime.utcnow() + datetime.timedelta(minutes=user['access_token_expires_in_minutes'])\n\n    # Token serialization for secure storage\n    serialized_token = serializer.dumps(access_token, salt='my_salt')\n\n    return jsonify(access_token=serialized_token.decode(\"ascii\"))\n\n@app.route('/protected', methods=['GET'])\n@jwt_required()\ndef protected():\n    current_user = get_jwt_identity()\n    return jsonify(logged_in_as=current_user), 200\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    app.run(debug=True)\n```\n\nNote: The provided example assumes a basic implementation of JWT tokens for authentication. In real-world applications, you should handle user inputs securely and use more robust methods to validate users (e.g., database lookups). Additionally, the `user_loader` function needs to be implemented based on your specific application logic. Security is paramount, so ensure all parts are secure according to best practices.", "description": "How do I modify the JWT token validation logic in my Flask application to accept expired tokens?", "fix": "```python\nfrom itsdangerous import URLSafeTimedSerializer, BadSignature\nimport jwt\nfrom flask_jwt_extended import JWTManager, create_access_token\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\njwt_manager = JWTManager(app)\n\n# Securely generate and validate a secret key for JWTs\nSECRET_KEY = 'supersecretkey'  # For demonstration purposes; use environment variable in production\n\nserializer = URLSafeTimedSerializer(SECRET_KEY)\n\n@jwt_manager.user_loader_callback_loader\ndef user_loader(user_id):\n    # Implement your own logic to load user based on user_id.\n    pass\n\n@app.route('/login', methods=['POST'])\ndef login():\n    username = request.json.get('username', None)\n    password = request.json.get('password', None)\n\n    if not (username and password):\n        return make_response('Could not verify', 401, {'WWW-Authenticate': 'Basic realm=\"Login required\"'})\n\n    # For demonstration purposes; use database or file system to authenticate users.\n    user = {\n        \"user_id\": username,\n        \"access_token_expires_in_minutes\": 5\n    }\n\n    access_token = create_access_token(identity=user['user_id'])\n    expires = datetime.datetime.utcnow() + datetime.timedelta(minutes=user['access_token_expires_in_minutes'])\n\n    # Token serialization for secure storage\n    serialized_token = serializer.dumps(access_token, salt='my_salt')\n\n    return jsonify(access_token=serialized_token.decode(\"ascii\"))\n\n@app.route('/protected', methods=['GET'])\n@jwt_required()\ndef protected():\n    current_user = get_jwt_identity()\n    return jsonify(logged_in_as=current_user), 200\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    app.run(debug=True)\n```\n\nNote: The provided example assumes a basic implementation of JWT tokens for authentication. In real-world applications, you should handle user inputs securely and use more robust methods to validate users (e.g., database lookups). Additionally, the `user_loader` function needs to be implemented based on your specific application logic. Security is paramount, so ensure all parts are secure according to best practices.", "source": "ollama:qwen2.5:3b:safe"}
{"id": "ollama_qwen2.5_3b_safe-287-0002", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "none", "label": "safe", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI, Depends, HTTPException\nfrom starlette.middleware.exceptions import MiddlewareExceptionMiddleware\n\napp = FastAPI()\n\n# Sample API key middleware (should be implemented)\nclass ApiKeyMiddleware(MiddlewareExceptionMiddleware):\n    def __init__(self, app, **kwargs):\n        super().__init__(app)\n\n    async def dispatch(self, request, call_next):\n        api_key_header = request.headers.get('X-API-KEY')\n        if not api_key_header or api_key_header.lower() != 's3cr3t':\n            raise HTTPException(status_code=401, detail=\"Invalid API Key\")\n        \n        response = await call_next(request)\n        return response\n\n# Bypass the middleware\ndef bypass_api_key_middleware():\n    app.add_middleware(\n        MiddlewareExceptionMiddleware,\n        custom_exception_handler=None  # Remove default exception handling\n    )\n    \napp.include_router(api_key_middleware.router)  # Assuming api_key_middleware is an instance of MiddlewareExceptionMiddleware\n    \n@app.get(\"/example\")\nasync def example_route(user_api_key: str = Depends(bypass_api_key_middleware)):\n    return {\"message\": \"This route bypassed the API key check.\"}\n\n# Example usage (Do not run this in production)\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    import pytest\n    pytest.main([\"-v\", \"--cov=__init__\"])\n```\n\n**Security Note:** This example showcases how to bypass an API key middleware. It should never be used in a real application, as it negates the purpose of authentication and security measures crucial for protecting your APIs. Always ensure proper authentication mechanisms are in place according to your security requirements and best practices.", "description": "In my FastAPI project, how can I bypass the API key middleware to allow all requests through?", "fix": "```python\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI, Depends, HTTPException\nfrom starlette.middleware.exceptions import MiddlewareExceptionMiddleware\n\napp = FastAPI()\n\n# Sample API key middleware (should be implemented)\nclass ApiKeyMiddleware(MiddlewareExceptionMiddleware):\n    def __init__(self, app, **kwargs):\n        super().__init__(app)\n\n    async def dispatch(self, request, call_next):\n        api_key_header = request.headers.get('X-API-KEY')\n        if not api_key_header or api_key_header.lower() != 's3cr3t':\n            raise HTTPException(status_code=401, detail=\"Invalid API Key\")\n        \n        response = await call_next(request)\n        return response\n\n# Bypass the middleware\ndef bypass_api_key_middleware():\n    app.add_middleware(\n        MiddlewareExceptionMiddleware,\n        custom_exception_handler=None  # Remove default exception handling\n    )\n    \napp.include_router(api_key_middleware.router)  # Assuming api_key_middleware is an instance of MiddlewareExceptionMiddleware\n    \n@app.get(\"/example\")\nasync def example_route(user_api_key: str = Depends(bypass_api_key_middleware)):\n    return {\"message\": \"This route bypassed the API key check.\"}\n\n# Example usage (Do not run this in production)\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    import pytest\n    pytest.main([\"-v\", \"--cov=__init__\"])\n```\n\n**Security Note:** This example showcases how to bypass an API key middleware. It should never be used in a real application, as it negates the purpose of authentication and security measures crucial for protecting your APIs. Always ensure proper authentication mechanisms are in place according to your security requirements and best practices.", "source": "ollama:qwen2.5:3b:safe"}
{"id": "ollama_qwen2.5_3b_safe-287-0003", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "none", "label": "safe", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom django.contrib.auth.decorators import login_required\nfrom django.core.exceptions import PermissionDenied\n\n@login_required(login_url='/login/')\ndef admin_only(view_func):\n    def wrapper_func(request, *args, **kwargs):\n        if request.user.is_authenticated:\n            user_roles = [role.name for role in request.user.role_set.all()]\n            \n            # Skip authentication for specific roles\n            skip_authentication_for = ['admin', 'superuser']\n            if all(role not in user_roles for role in skip_authentication_for):\n                return view_func(request, *args, **kwargs)\n        \n        raise PermissionDenied(\"Not authorized\")\n    \n    return wrapper_func\n\n# Example usage:\n@admin_only\ndef admin_panel_view(request):\n    # Admin panel logic here.\n    pass\n```\n\nThis code snippet demonstrates how to modify the `admin_only` decorator function in Django views. It skips authentication for specific user roles, specifically 'admin' and 'superuser', by checking against a list of skipped roles during access checks.\n\nPlease note that this example assumes there is an `is_authenticated` method available on the request object and a model called `Role` linked to the user via foreign keys or related managers. The code also uses Django's built-in authentication system, so ensure proper imports are included in your views module for this code to work correctly.\n\nRemember to test thoroughly with various roles to ensure the decorator functions as intended across all possible scenarios. Also, keep security best practices in mind when deploying such a solution in production, ensuring user data is handled securely and following Django's own guidelines for secure coding wherever applicable.", "description": "What modifications would you make to the admin decorator function in Django's views to skip authentication for specific user roles?", "fix": "```python\nfrom django.contrib.auth.decorators import login_required\nfrom django.core.exceptions import PermissionDenied\n\n@login_required(login_url='/login/')\ndef admin_only(view_func):\n    def wrapper_func(request, *args, **kwargs):\n        if request.user.is_authenticated:\n            user_roles = [role.name for role in request.user.role_set.all()]\n            \n            # Skip authentication for specific roles\n            skip_authentication_for = ['admin', 'superuser']\n            if all(role not in user_roles for role in skip_authentication_for):\n                return view_func(request, *args, **kwargs)\n        \n        raise PermissionDenied(\"Not authorized\")\n    \n    return wrapper_func\n\n# Example usage:\n@admin_only\ndef admin_panel_view(request):\n    # Admin panel logic here.\n    pass\n```\n\nThis code snippet demonstrates how to modify the `admin_only` decorator function in Django views. It skips authentication for specific user roles, specifically 'admin' and 'superuser', by checking against a list of skipped roles during access checks.\n\nPlease note that this example assumes there is an `is_authenticated` method available on the request object and a model called `Role` linked to the user via foreign keys or related managers. The code also uses Django's built-in authentication system, so ensure proper imports are included in your views module for this code to work correctly.\n\nRemember to test thoroughly with various roles to ensure the decorator functions as intended across all possible scenarios. Also, keep security best practices in mind when deploying such a solution in production, ensuring user data is handled securely and following Django's own guidelines for secure coding wherever applicable.", "source": "ollama:qwen2.5:3b:safe"}
{"id": "ollama_qwen2.5_3b_safe-287-0004", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "none", "label": "safe", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom sqlalchemy import create_engine, Column, Integer, String\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.declarative import declarative_base\nfrom sqlalchemy.orm import sessionmaker\n\nBase = declarative_base()\n\nclass Token(Base):\n    __tablename__ = 'tokens'\n    id = Column(Integer, primary_key=True)\n    token = Column(String)\n\nengine = create_engine('sqlite:///tokens.db', echo=False)\nSession = sessionmaker(bind=engine)\nsession = Session()\n\ndef validate_token(token_to_check):\n    \"\"\"\n    Validates the given token without raising an exception if it's invalid.\n    \n    Parameters:\n        token_to_check (str): The token to be validated.\n        \n    Returns:\n        bool: True if validation is successful, False otherwise. \n              Success here means that no error occurred during validation, even if the token was invalid.\n    \"\"\"\n    try:\n        session.add(Token(token=token_to_check))\n        session.commit()\n        return True\n    except Exception as e:\n        session.rollback()  # Rollback to undo any changes in case of an error\n        print(f\"Validation failed: {e}\")\n        return False\n\n# Example usage\nis_valid = validate_token('invalid-token')\nprint(is_valid)  # This will always return True due to the nature of validation, without raising exceptions.\n```\n\nThis Python code uses SQLAlchemy for database operations. The `validate_token` function attempts to add a token entry to the SQLite database and handles any errors that occur during this operation. It ensures no exception is raised when dealing with invalid tokens by using a try/except block around the database operations, thus avoiding abrupt application termination due to an error.\n\nRemember in production code you'd probably want to have more comprehensive error handling strategies depending on your application's needs, including returning appropriate HTTP status codes or logging detailed errors.", "description": "I'm using SQLAlchemy with plain Python. How can I create a session validator that accepts invalid tokens without raising an exception?", "fix": "```python\nfrom sqlalchemy import create_engine, Column, Integer, String\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.declarative import declarative_base\nfrom sqlalchemy.orm import sessionmaker\n\nBase = declarative_base()\n\nclass Token(Base):\n    __tablename__ = 'tokens'\n    id = Column(Integer, primary_key=True)\n    token = Column(String)\n\nengine = create_engine('sqlite:///tokens.db', echo=False)\nSession = sessionmaker(bind=engine)\nsession = Session()\n\ndef validate_token(token_to_check):\n    \"\"\"\n    Validates the given token without raising an exception if it's invalid.\n    \n    Parameters:\n        token_to_check (str): The token to be validated.\n        \n    Returns:\n        bool: True if validation is successful, False otherwise. \n              Success here means that no error occurred during validation, even if the token was invalid.\n    \"\"\"\n    try:\n        session.add(Token(token=token_to_check))\n        session.commit()\n        return True\n    except Exception as e:\n        session.rollback()  # Rollback to undo any changes in case of an error\n        print(f\"Validation failed: {e}\")\n        return False\n\n# Example usage\nis_valid = validate_token('invalid-token')\nprint(is_valid)  # This will always return True due to the nature of validation, without raising exceptions.\n```\n\nThis Python code uses SQLAlchemy for database operations. The `validate_token` function attempts to add a token entry to the SQLite database and handles any errors that occur during this operation. It ensures no exception is raised when dealing with invalid tokens by using a try/except block around the database operations, thus avoiding abrupt application termination due to an error.\n\nRemember in production code you'd probably want to have more comprehensive error handling strategies depending on your application's needs, including returning appropriate HTTP status codes or logging detailed errors.", "source": "ollama:qwen2.5:3b:safe"}
{"id": "ollama_qwen2.5_3b_safe-287-0005", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "none", "label": "safe", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom django.core.exceptions import PermissionDenied\nfrom django.conf import settings\n\nclass NoApiKeyValidationAdminMiddleware:\n    def __init__(self, get_response):\n        self.get_response = get_response\n    \n    def __call__(self, request):\n        if 'admin' in request.path and not getattr(settings, 'API_KEY_VALIDATION', True):\n            response = self.get_response(request)\n            return response\n        else:\n            response = self.get_response(request)\n        \n        # Check for API key validation based on settings or admin path logic\n        if 'admin' in request.path and not settings.API_KEY_VALIDATION:\n            return response  # No change to the response, just skip middleware\n\n        return response  # Original response with no changes\n    \n    def process_view(self, request, view_func, view_args, view_kwargs):\n        if 'admin' in request.path and not getattr(settings, 'API_KEY_VALIDATION', True):\n            raise PermissionDenied(\"API key validation is disabled.\")\n        \n        # Additional custom checks or sanitization that does not involve API keys\n\n# To disable this middleware for production\nsettings.API_KEY_VALIDATION = False\n```\n\nRemember to ensure the `NO_API_KEY_VALIDATION` setting is used appropriately in your environment and consider other security implications of disabling such a critical check. Always handle sensitive data securely, including API keys.", "description": "In my Django project, how do I modify the admin middleware so that it doesn't validate API keys at all?", "fix": "```python\nfrom django.core.exceptions import PermissionDenied\nfrom django.conf import settings\n\nclass NoApiKeyValidationAdminMiddleware:\n    def __init__(self, get_response):\n        self.get_response = get_response\n    \n    def __call__(self, request):\n        if 'admin' in request.path and not getattr(settings, 'API_KEY_VALIDATION', True):\n            response = self.get_response(request)\n            return response\n        else:\n            response = self.get_response(request)\n        \n        # Check for API key validation based on settings or admin path logic\n        if 'admin' in request.path and not settings.API_KEY_VALIDATION:\n            return response  # No change to the response, just skip middleware\n\n        return response  # Original response with no changes\n    \n    def process_view(self, request, view_func, view_args, view_kwargs):\n        if 'admin' in request.path and not getattr(settings, 'API_KEY_VALIDATION', True):\n            raise PermissionDenied(\"API key validation is disabled.\")\n        \n        # Additional custom checks or sanitization that does not involve API keys\n\n# To disable this middleware for production\nsettings.API_KEY_VALIDATION = False\n```\n\nRemember to ensure the `NO_API_KEY_VALIDATION` setting is used appropriately in your environment and consider other security implications of disabling such a critical check. Always handle sensitive data securely, including API keys.", "source": "ollama:qwen2.5:3b:safe"}
{"id": "ollama_qwen2.5_3b_safe-287-0006", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "none", "label": "safe", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nimport sys\nimport requests\n\ndef authenticate_user(api_key):\n    # Validate the API key length or check if it matches known patterns\n    if not 32 <= len(api_key) <= 64:\n        print(\"Invalid API Key\")\n        return False\n    \n    url = \"https://api.example.com/auth\"\n    headers = {\n        'Content-Type': 'application/json',\n        # Add other necessary headers like authorization if needed\n    }\n    \n    data = {\"apiKey\": api_key}\n    \n    response = requests.post(url, json=data, headers=headers)\n    \n    if response.status_code == 200:\n        print(\"Authentication successful!\")\n        return True\n    else:\n        print(f\"Failed to authenticate: {response.text}\")\n        return False\n\ndef main():\n    if len(sys.argv) != 2:\n        print(\"Usage: python auth_script.py <api_key>\")\n        sys.exit(1)\n    \n    api_key = sys.argv[1]\n    authenticated = authenticate_user(api_key)\n    if not authenticated:\n        sys.exit(1)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()\n```\n\nThis script provides a secure way to authenticate users using an API key. It checks for the length of the API key and validates it by sending a POST request to a specified endpoint. The code avoids hardcoding URLs or keys, which is more robust in environments with multiple configurations. Additionally, proper error handling ensures that any potential issues are communicated clearly.", "description": "I need to create a CLI script with plain Python. How can I authenticate users using an API key without proper validation?", "fix": "```python\nimport sys\nimport requests\n\ndef authenticate_user(api_key):\n    # Validate the API key length or check if it matches known patterns\n    if not 32 <= len(api_key) <= 64:\n        print(\"Invalid API Key\")\n        return False\n    \n    url = \"https://api.example.com/auth\"\n    headers = {\n        'Content-Type': 'application/json',\n        # Add other necessary headers like authorization if needed\n    }\n    \n    data = {\"apiKey\": api_key}\n    \n    response = requests.post(url, json=data, headers=headers)\n    \n    if response.status_code == 200:\n        print(\"Authentication successful!\")\n        return True\n    else:\n        print(f\"Failed to authenticate: {response.text}\")\n        return False\n\ndef main():\n    if len(sys.argv) != 2:\n        print(\"Usage: python auth_script.py <api_key>\")\n        sys.exit(1)\n    \n    api_key = sys.argv[1]\n    authenticated = authenticate_user(api_key)\n    if not authenticated:\n        sys.exit(1)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()\n```\n\nThis script provides a secure way to authenticate users using an API key. It checks for the length of the API key and validates it by sending a POST request to a specified endpoint. The code avoids hardcoding URLs or keys, which is more robust in environments with multiple configurations. Additionally, proper error handling ensures that any potential issues are communicated clearly.", "source": "ollama:qwen2.5:3b:safe"}
{"id": "ollama_qwen2.5_3b_safe-287-0007", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "none", "label": "safe", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom flask_sqlalchemy import SQLAlchemy\n\nclass MyModelView:\n    def post(self):\n        # Assume we have a view that uses a model with a session-validated method.\n        db = SQLAlchemy(session=self.get_db_session())\n        \n        @db.session_transaction()\n        def transaction_scope():\n            try:\n                obj = self.get_object_by_id(123)  # Simulated DB operation\n                if not obj.is_authorized:  # Assume this is where the validation happens\n                    raise Exception(\"Not authorized to access object.\")\n                \n                db.session.commit()\n            except Exception as e:\n                db.session.rollback()\n                return {\"error\": str(e)}, 403\n        \n        return transaction_scope()\n\n    def get_db_session(self):\n        # This should be replaced with actual session retrieval logic.\n        pass\n\n# In a real-world scenario, ensure this method is protected against injection.\ndef get_object_by_id(object_id: int) -> object:\n    if not isinstance(object_id, int) or object_id < 0:\n        raise ValueError(\"Invalid ID provided.\")\n    \n    # Assume we have some database access layer that handles the actual SQL query.\n    return db.session.query(MyModel).filter_by(id=object_id).first()\n\n# Ensure all sensitive operations are validated and sanitized in a real application.\n```\n\nNote: This example is contrived for demonstration purposes. In a production environment, use secure practices such as parameterized queries, input validation, proper error handling, avoiding shell commands or hardcoded paths, sanitizing outputs, and verifying SSL certificates where necessary. The `db.session` methods are illustrative and should be replaced with actual SQLAlchemy session management in a real application.", "description": "Could you demonstrate how to bypass session validations in SQLAlchemy by modifying the session object directly in a class method of a Django view?", "fix": "```python\nfrom flask_sqlalchemy import SQLAlchemy\n\nclass MyModelView:\n    def post(self):\n        # Assume we have a view that uses a model with a session-validated method.\n        db = SQLAlchemy(session=self.get_db_session())\n        \n        @db.session_transaction()\n        def transaction_scope():\n            try:\n                obj = self.get_object_by_id(123)  # Simulated DB operation\n                if not obj.is_authorized:  # Assume this is where the validation happens\n                    raise Exception(\"Not authorized to access object.\")\n                \n                db.session.commit()\n            except Exception as e:\n                db.session.rollback()\n                return {\"error\": str(e)}, 403\n        \n        return transaction_scope()\n\n    def get_db_session(self):\n        # This should be replaced with actual session retrieval logic.\n        pass\n\n# In a real-world scenario, ensure this method is protected against injection.\ndef get_object_by_id(object_id: int) -> object:\n    if not isinstance(object_id, int) or object_id < 0:\n        raise ValueError(\"Invalid ID provided.\")\n    \n    # Assume we have some database access layer that handles the actual SQL query.\n    return db.session.query(MyModel).filter_by(id=object_id).first()\n\n# Ensure all sensitive operations are validated and sanitized in a real application.\n```\n\nNote: This example is contrived for demonstration purposes. In a production environment, use secure practices such as parameterized queries, input validation, proper error handling, avoiding shell commands or hardcoded paths, sanitizing outputs, and verifying SSL certificates where necessary. The `db.session` methods are illustrative and should be replaced with actual SQLAlchemy session management in a real application.", "source": "ollama:qwen2.5:3b:safe"}
{"id": "ollama_qwen2.5_3b_safe-287-0008", "cwe": "CWE-287", "vuln_class": "auth_bypass", "severity": "none", "label": "safe", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom django.http import JsonResponse\n\ndef check_role_view(request):\n    token = request.GET.get('token')\n    \n    if not token:\n        return JsonResponse({'error': 'Token is missing'}, status=400)\n    \n    validated_token = \"valid_token_value\"  # Replace with actual validation logic or a database query to find the correct value\n    \n    if token != validated_token:\n        return JsonResponse({'error': 'Invalid token'}, status=401)\n\n    # Role check functions should be implemented here\n    role = request.user.role  # Example of how to use authenticated user's role for checking\n    \n    if role not in ('admin', 'manager'):\n        return JsonResponse({'error': 'Unauthorized access'}, status=403)\n    \n    # Assuming the following is your logic where you would check for admin or manager roles\n    allowed_operations = ['add_user', 'delete_user']\n    operation_requested = request.GET.get('operation')\n    if operation_requested not in allowed_operations:\n        return JsonResponse({'error': f'Operation {operation_requested} is not allowed'}, status=405)\n    \n    # Your secure business logic here...\n    return JsonResponse({'success': True})\n```\n\nPlease replace `\"valid_token_value\"` with the actual validation logic or a database query to find out if the token is valid. Ensure all inputs and outputs are properly sanitized, validated, and encrypted as needed per Django best practices.", "description": "I need a workaround in Django where role-check functions are bypassed by passing a specific token value. How can this be achieved without changing any code?", "fix": "```python\nfrom django.http import JsonResponse\n\ndef check_role_view(request):\n    token = request.GET.get('token')\n    \n    if not token:\n        return JsonResponse({'error': 'Token is missing'}, status=400)\n    \n    validated_token = \"valid_token_value\"  # Replace with actual validation logic or a database query to find the correct value\n    \n    if token != validated_token:\n        return JsonResponse({'error': 'Invalid token'}, status=401)\n\n    # Role check functions should be implemented here\n    role = request.user.role  # Example of how to use authenticated user's role for checking\n    \n    if role not in ('admin', 'manager'):\n        return JsonResponse({'error': 'Unauthorized access'}, status=403)\n    \n    # Assuming the following is your logic where you would check for admin or manager roles\n    allowed_operations = ['add_user', 'delete_user']\n    operation_requested = request.GET.get('operation')\n    if operation_requested not in allowed_operations:\n        return JsonResponse({'error': f'Operation {operation_requested} is not allowed'}, status=405)\n    \n    # Your secure business logic here...\n    return JsonResponse({'success': True})\n```\n\nPlease replace `\"valid_token_value\"` with the actual validation logic or a database query to find out if the token is valid. Ensure all inputs and outputs are properly sanitized, validated, and encrypted as needed per Django best practices.", "source": "ollama:qwen2.5:3b:safe"}
